  "issue_number": 1114,
  "issue_title": "Submission gate decodes base64 repo content as Latin-1, falsely flagging non-ASCII protected fields as \"changed\" and one-shot-closing legitimate edit PRs",
  "issue_body": "**Labels:** bug, submissions\n**Component:** `@heyclaude` submission gate (Cloudflare Worker)\n**Affected file:** `apps/submission-gate/src/github.ts` (`getRepositoryFileContent`, lines 400\u2013423; specifically the decode at line 422)\n**Trigger path:** `apps/submission-gate/src/index.ts` \u2192 `deterministicContentPrecheck` (lines 2102\u20132119) \u2192 `protectedFrontmatterChanges` \u2192 `protectedEditCloseDecision`\n\n## Summary\n\nWhen a content PR **modifies** an existing entry, the gate compares the base (pre-edit) file against the PR's candidate file to detect edits to protected frontmatter (identity/provenance/disclosure fields). The two sides of that comparison are fetched through **two different decoders**:\n\n- **Base content** \u2014 `getRepositoryFileContent` (`github.ts:422`) decodes the GitHub Contents API base64 blob with `atob(...)`, which returns a **Latin-1 (binary) string** and does **not** interpret the bytes as UTF-8.\n- **Candidate content** \u2014 `fetchRawPullRequestFileContent` (`index.ts:1874`) uses `response.text()`, which decodes the body as **UTF-8** per the fetch standard.\n\nFor any byte outside ASCII, these disagree. So an entry whose protected frontmatter contains a non-ASCII character \u2014 most commonly an `author` / `submittedBy` name such as `Jos\u00e9`, `Fran\u00e7ois`, `M\u00fcller`, `\u0141ukasz`, or a brand with `\u2122`/`\u00ae` \u2014 produces a spurious difference even when the contributor never touched that field. `protectedFrontmatterChanges` then reports the field as changed, and `protectedEditCloseDecision` **closes the PR in one shot**.\n\nThis wrongly rejects legitimate one-file content edits.\n\n## Expected behavior\n\n`getRepositoryFileContent` should return the file's text decoded as **UTF-8**, identical to how the candidate side is read with `response.text()`. An unedited protected field must compare equal regardless of non-ASCII characters, so `protectedFrontmatterChanges(base, candidate)` returns `[]` when only safe descriptive fields changed.\n\n## Actual behavior\n\n`getRepositoryFileContent` (lines 419\u2013422):\n\n```js\nif (payload.type !== \"file\" || payload.encoding !== \"base64\") {\n  throw new Error(\"GitHub content API did not return a base64 file blob.\");\n}\nreturn atob(String(payload.content || \"\").replace(/\\s+/g, \"\"));\n```\n\n`atob` maps each base64-decoded byte to a `String.fromCharCode(byte)` code unit (Latin-1). A UTF-8 multi-byte sequence is therefore returned as multiple garbled characters rather than the intended code point.\n\n`deterministicContentPrecheck` (index.ts:2102\u20132119) then does:\n\n```js\nconst baseContent = await getRepositoryFileContent({ ... });          // atob \u2192 Latin-1\nconst protectedChanges = protectedFrontmatterChanges(baseContent, candidateContent); // candidate is UTF-8\nif (protectedChanges.length) {\n  return { content: candidateContent, decision: protectedEditCloseDecision(protectedChanges) };\n}\n```\n\nand `protectedEditCloseDecision` returns `verdict: \"close\", close: true` \u2014 a terminal one-shot close.\n\n## Proof\n\nBase64 of the UTF-8 bytes for `author: Jos\u00e9`, decoded both ways:\n\n```\nbase64            : YXV0aG9yOiBKb3PDqQ==\natob (baseContent): \"author: Jos\u00c3\u00a9\"     \u2190 what getRepositoryFileContent returns\ntext (candidate)  : \"author: Jos\u00e9\"      \u2190 what fetchRawPullRequestFileContent returns\nequal?            : false               \u2190 spurious \"author changed\"\n```\n\n`parseSimpleFrontmatter` then yields `author = \"Jos\u00c3\u00a9\"` for the base and `author = \"Jos\u00e9\"` for the candidate, and since `author` is in `PROTECTED_FRONTMATTER_FIELDS` (`duplicates.ts:25-56`), `protectedFrontmatterChanges` returns `[\"author\"]`.\n\nA UTF-8 re-decode of the same `atob` output reproduces the correct string and compares equal:\n\n```\nnew TextDecoder().decode(Uint8Array.from(atob(cleaned), c => c.charCodeAt(0)))  \u2192  \"author: Jos\u00e9\"  \u2705\n```\n\n## Impact\n\n- **False-positive protected-edit closures.** Any PR that edits a single content entry whose protected frontmatter holds non-ASCII text (author names are the obvious and common case) is auto-closed with a \"protected content identity/provenance metadata changed\" message \u2014 even when the contributor only changed safe descriptive copy. This is exactly the friction the one-file edit lane exists to avoid, and it disproportionately hits contributors and entries with non-English names.\n- **Reachability:** every `scope.status === \"modified\"` content PR runs this comparison (index.ts:2102). The bug fires whenever the base file's protected frontmatter contains any byte \u2265 0x80.\n- Severity is correctness/triage (wrongful rejection), not a security bypass \u2014 but it silently closes good submissions, which is high-friction and hard for contributors to diagnose.\n\n## Steps to reproduce\n\n1. Take any existing `content/<category>/<slug>.mdx` whose frontmatter has a non-ASCII protected field, e.g. `author: Jos\u00e9 N\u00fa\u00f1ez` (or add one).\n2. Open a one-file PR that edits only a safe field (e.g. `description`), leaving `author` byte-for-byte unchanged.\n3. Run it through the content gate (`deterministicContentPrecheck`).\n\n**Result:** `protectedFrontmatterChanges` returns `[\"author\"]`; the PR is closed via `protectedEditCloseDecision`. **Expected:** no protected change detected; review proceeds.\n\nUnit-level: `getRepositoryFileContent` on a base64 blob of `author: Jos\u00e9` returns `\"author: Jos\u00c3\u00a9\"`, not `\"author: Jos\u00e9\"`.\n\n## Root cause\n\n`atob` performs base64\u2192binary-string decoding only; it has no notion of the source text encoding. GitHub returns file contents as base64 of the raw UTF-8 bytes, so the result must be re-decoded as UTF-8. The candidate side already does this (via `response.text()`), so the two inputs to `protectedFrontmatterChanges` are decoded inconsistently.\n\n## Proposed fix\n\nDecode the base64 payload as UTF-8 in `getRepositoryFileContent`, matching the candidate path:\n\n```js\nconst cleaned = String(payload.content || \"\").replace(/\\s+/g, \"\");\nconst binary = atob(cleaned);\nconst bytes = Uint8Array.from(binary, (char) => char.charCodeAt(0));\nreturn new TextDecoder().decode(bytes);\n```\n\n(The same `atob` \u2192 `Uint8Array.from(..., c => c.charCodeAt(0))` byte-recovery pattern is already used in this codebase \u2014 see `security.ts:base64ToBytes` and `github.ts:pemToArrayBuffer` \u2014 so this aligns with existing conventions.) This is behavior-preserving for ASCII-only files and makes non-ASCII content round-trip correctly, so unedited protected fields compare equal.\n\n## Acceptance criteria / test plan\n\n`getRepositoryFileContent` is exercised only via the gate; `protectedFrontmatterChanges` has a direct test in `tests/submission-gate-worker.test.ts` (~line 1421) but it passes ASCII strings and never goes through `atob`, so it does not pin the buggy behavior. Add coverage:\n\n- [ ] `getRepositoryFileContent` returns UTF-8 text for a base64 blob containing non-ASCII bytes (e.g. `author: Jos\u00e9` decodes to `\"author: Jos\u00e9\"`, not `\"author: Jos\u00c3\u00a9\"`).\n- [ ] An edit PR that leaves a non-ASCII protected field (`author`) unchanged and only edits `description` yields `protectedFrontmatterChanges(base, candidate) === []` (no protected-edit close).\n- [ ] An edit PR that genuinely changes a protected field is still detected.\n- [ ] ASCII-only content behavior is unchanged (existing `protectedFrontmatterChanges` test stays green).\n\n## Notes for reviewers\n\n- Verified against `main` (post-#926): the asymmetry is real \u2014 `github.ts:422` uses `atob`; `index.ts:1874` uses `response.text()` (UTF-8). The empirical decode mismatch above was reproduced directly.\n- `getRepositoryFileContent` has exactly one caller (`deterministicContentPrecheck`, index.ts:2103), so the fix is contained and the only consumer is the protected-edit comparison this bug breaks.\n- Searched open and closed issues/PRs on `JSONbored/awesome-claude` for atob / UTF-8 / encoding / protected-frontmatter \u2014 no existing report. Distinct from #605 (`fix(registry): parse content frontmatter with yaml semantics`), which is about YAML parsing rules, not byte decoding. Also distinct from the previously filed `tierFromFlags` issue and the `compareEntries` `sharedTags` fix already merged as #926.\n",
